title: For Sale:  M1 Garand IHC
postcontent: A very late model Garand with all of the improvements of this type. IHC manufactured approximately 337,623 of the total 5,468,772 rifles produced since 1936, if you believe Scott Duff's research into the matter. This one bears a date of the 307th day of 1954 from the Julian date stamped into the inside of the stock when the wood was tooled out by the Frank Overton Company. Line Materials made the barrel. They set out to produce among the finest barrels ever put on a Garand. This is arguably the scarcest Garand to be had and this one is just about as-issued in 1954, save probably the handguards have almost assuredly been replaced at some point. The MW is a 2.8 approximately and the TE is a 4 and the bore is shiney from one end to the other. Obviously this particular rifle never saw a hostile environment in its 61 year history.

title: For Sale:  WATCH OUT FOR REMAN AMMO.
location: Myrtle Beach, Myrtle Beach, South Carolina
postcontent:
At a local range the other day guy was shooting some no name REMANUFACTURED ammunition. Kept jamming in his 1911. Stood multiple boxes of rounds up on end some was so stretched cases, crack necks, swings. Stood them side by side looked like the N.Y. Skyline. Take a micrometer with you or a reloading gauge and measure the cases. Personally if it's not factory I don't carry it for self defense, practice my own reloads only. If your carry reloads for self defense consult your lawyer.I know of at least 6 cases of guys that ended up in prison for using reloads that were hot or weak or even different brands of cases than what was left as evidence to test. 

BUY and USE AT YOUR OWN RISK.
